Raw dev notes -- The AI Agent Platform: From Secrets to Chat UI and Beyond

**Project Background:**
This project, internally dubbed the "Master Control Program" for AI agents, is all about building out our internal platform for leveraging large language models. The goal is to provide a robust, secure, and user-friendly environment where our teams can deploy and interact with specialized AI agents, ultimately streamlining complex internal workflows and decision-making.

**What was done:**
This past week was a whirlwind, touching almost every part of the stack. A major win was getting the Llama 3.3 70B model fully uploaded to our cluster's PVC and registered with the WAIP UI – finally, a big model ready for action! I also spent a good chunk of time hardening our model download process, adding auto-cleanup for stale processes and making the parsing more robust, which should prevent a lot of headaches down the line.

Secrets management got a significant overhaul. I migrated a dozen keys to Windows Credential Manager and implemented an additive hybrid config system, allowing for a slow, safe migration away from `.env` files. This was a big step towards better security posture, and I even added a self-test command for the config.

On the agent front, the "planning agent" saw massive progress. I integrated source materials, mapped out a vertical decision tree, and mocked up the full workflow in Excel. There was a lot of back-and-forth with Sahar, incorporating feedback, resolving conflicts, and updating diagrams – even building an interactive version, which was a fun little frontend challenge (and a pain with JS string escaping!). I also added schema-hash drift detection for its critical data exports.

The user-facing chat UI (OWUI) was a huge focus. I got the backend for `org-chat` complete and started on the HTML/n8n integration. The `chat-ui` itself now has persistent chat history, per-user isolation, and the ability to rename conversations. A big milestone was getting file uploads working, including proxying multipart data, pre-warming extraction, and adding sticky attachments with per-bubble badges. I even confirmed our XLSX capability matches ChatGPT's, which was a relief after some initial head-scratching. Admin features like approving pending signups via CLI were also added. We also migrated all our live hostnames to the new `*.ai.rh.tech` domain, which involved a bit of TLS wrangling. Finally, I built out an LLM-driven content-based file renaming capability, which is pretty neat.

Security wasn't forgotten either; I implemented a `PreToolUse` hook to block agents from writing to our shared network drive and moved it to a user-global scope. Also added a PII scrubber for session JSONL data.

**What was hard or surprising:**
The secrets migration, while necessary, was a bit of a beast. Trying to implement an "additive hybrid" approach without breaking existing functionality meant a lot of careful testing and a "slow-migration policy" that felt like walking on eggshells. The auto-cleanup for stale sibling processes in the model downloader was also trickier than expected, requiring `psutil` and careful handling of process lifecycles.

The `planning-agent` interactive diagram was a classic "simple feature, complex implementation" scenario – debugging unterminated JavaScript strings and backtick issues for titles felt like a blast from the past. Also, the iterative nature of working with stakeholders like Sahar on the planning agent, with new decisions and conflicts popping up, really highlighted the dynamic nature of requirements gathering.

Initially, I hit a snag with file upload capabilities, thinking we might be behind ChatGPT on XLSX processing. Turns out, it was a stale script path, and once that was fixed, we were on par. That was a good reminder to double-check the basics before diving into complex root cause analysis. The hostname migration also needed a "round 2 + TLS fix," which is always fun when you're dealing with live services.

**Personal Reflection:**
This period felt like a sprint across the entire project. It was exhilarating to see so many disparate pieces come together – from low-level infrastructure like model deployment and secrets, to core agent logic, and finally to a polished, user-facing chat interface with advanced features like file uploads and persistent history. There were moments of frustration, especially with the fiddly bits of frontend JS or the subtle bugs in process management, but the satisfaction of seeing it all click into place was immense. It really reinforced the idea that building a comprehensive platform requires a holistic approach, where security, user experience, and core functionality are all developed in parallel. I'm proud of the progress, especially how much the chat UI has matured.

**What's next:**
Focus on OWUI RAG, vision, and extraction, with Docling integration.
